  "prompt": "Why do I always feel a headache?",
  "response": "I'm not a doctor, but there are several potential reasons you might be experiencing frequent headaches. Here are some possibilities:\n\n1. **Tension Headaches**: Stress, poor posture, or muscle tension can lead to tension-type headaches.\n\n2. **Migraines**: These are often severe and can be triggered by various factors, including certain foods, hormonal changes, or environmental factors.\n\n3. **Rebound Headaches**: Overuse of pain medications can lead to rebound headaches, where headaches become more frequent.\n\n4. **Dehydration**: Not drinking enough water can cause headaches.\n\n5. **Sinus Issues**: Sinus infections or allergies can lead to sinus headaches.\n\n6. **Eye Strain**: Extended periods of screen time without breaks can contribute to headaches.\n\n7. **Sleep Problems**: Poor sleep quality or sleep disorders can trigger headaches.\n\n8. **Dietary Factors**: Skipping meals or certain food sensitivities can lead to headaches.\n\n9. **Caffeine Withdrawal**: If you're used to consuming caffeine regularly and skip it, withdrawal can cause headaches.\n\n10. **Medical Conditions**: Sometimes, headaches can be a sign of an underlying medical condition, such as hypertension or neurological issues.\n\nIf your headaches are frequent, persistent, or worsening, consider consulting a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment. They can help identify the cause and suggest tailored interventions.",
